fix(backup): use sudo -u postgres + PIPESTATUS + size threshold

Two bugs caught on first prod backup-db.sh run (root@cv6067007):

1. pg_dump peer-auth failed for eclipse_chat_user
   Script ran as root via sudo, but pg_hba.conf requires peer
   match (OS user <-> PG user) on Unix socket. Root has no PG
   role named eclipse_chat_user.

   Fix: invoke pg_dump as `sudo -u postgres pg_dump <db>`. OS
   user `postgres` maps to PG superuser `postgres` via peer auth,
   which has read access to every database. No password / no env
   var needed, no .pgpass churn.

2. 20-byte empty-gzip file passed sanity check
   Original guard was `[[ ! -s "$OUT" ]]` (file size > 0). But
   gzip-of-empty-input still emits ~20 bytes of gzip header, so
   the guard never fired. Combined with bug #1 the bad file was
   accepted as a successful backup.

   Fixes:
   - Check ${PIPESTATUS[0]} after pg_dump | gzip pipe. set -o
     pipefail wouldn't catch this on its own — gzip exits 0 on
     empty stream, masking the real pg_dump failure.
   - Raise sanity threshold to 100 bytes. Even an empty Postgres
     dump is way larger than that (header SET statements alone).

Side effects: removed `-U "$DB_USER"` from pg_dump invocation —
not needed when running as superuser. ECLIPSE_DB_USER env var
stays defined in script header for documentation, but unused.

Verified locally: typecheck doesn't apply (shell script). Will
verify on prod by Pavel re-running the script after pulling.

